{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014uHBE8YSpUSVWrXBEFvgaD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is signature verification logic — comparing HMAC-SHA256 of raw body against header. The failure mode is in the verification function itself and the handler's response to it. This could be a single function boundary.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. The HMAC computation is deterministic and in-process.\n- MOCK-HIDE: The signature check is pure crypto logic + HTTP response code. Could be tested with a fake HTTP request.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n\nThe signature verification itself is Unit-testable, but the full behavior—rejecting with 401 and preventing forwarding—requires testing the HTTP handler's integration with the signature verifier and queue logic, making this Integration level.\n\nFor the second behavior about queue writes preceding the HTTP 200 response, I need to verify the ordering of operations within the handler. A mocked queue lets me track when the write occurs relative to when the response is sent, so I can confirm the sequence without needing real infrastructure.\n\nThe third behavior tests that the handler responds without waiting for downstream processing to complete. I can use an in-process mock downstream with an artificial delay to verify the response arrives before that processing finishes.\n\nFor the fourth behavior about response latency under concurrent load, I'm starting to think through how to test that the response stays under 3 seconds even when earlier events are still being processed downstream. The wall-clock timing under concurrent load is really the crux here — I keep going back and forth on whether this needs true system-level testing or if an in-process mock with real timers would suffice. The core failure is about event-loop blocking while waiting for a slow downstream service, which I can actually test in-process using setTimeout delays. So this lands in Integration territory, though the concurrent aspect and real timing requirements make it feel borderline.\n\nNow looking at the next behavior around duplicate event IDs and queue writes. idempotency — checking if an event ID was already seen. This involves the handler + some deduplication store (persistent or in-memory).\n- REAL-INFRA: If the deduplication store is persistent (database), this needs Integration. If it's in-memory, could be Unit.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Depends on implementation. If using a real DB for dedup, need real DB or in-process fake.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- Assessment: Integration — needs the handler + deduplication store to work together. The \"already received\" implies some persistent or in-memory state that needs to be checked.\n\n**Behavior 6**: When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests handler behavior when queue returns a \"full\" error. The queue itself can be mocked to return a full error.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real infra needed. Mock queue returning a full condition is sufficient.\n- MOCK-HIDE: The mock queue triggers the error condition. The handler's response (503 + Retry-After header) is what's being tested.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- Assessment: Integration — handler + mock queue interaction.\n\n**Behavior 7**: The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests the queue implementation itself — not the handler, but the queue's own capacity enforcement.\n- REAL-INFRA: If the queue is a real external system (Redis, Kafka, etc.), this would be System. If it's an in-process implementation, it could be Integration or even Unit.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If the queue is mocked, this behavior can't be tested at all — you'd be testing the mock. This MUST use a real queue implementation.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- Assessment: Integration if using a real in-process queue, System if using an external queue. the queue is an in-process module. System if the queue is an external service (Redis, Kafka). Given the behavior says \"persistent queue\" — it sounds external, so System. But the behavior could also describe an internal queue module with persistence.\n\nThe behavior says \"persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit\" — the word \"actually\" suggests this needs the real thing, not a mock. If it's an external queue service, System. If internal, Integration. I'll say System as the minimum, since \"persistent queue\" implies real persistence (disk, external service).\n\nActually, let me reconsider. \"Persistent queue\" could mean a local SQLite or file-based queue, which would be Integration (local filesystem). Or it could be Redis/Kafka which would be System (real external service). Given the context (webhook handler with internal processing queue), it could go either way. I'll lean toward System since \"persistent\" implies real storage and the failure would only appear with the actual queue implementation.\n\nSo my final breakdown is: signature validation and queue writes need Integration tests with mocks, the non-awaiting behavior needs a slow downstream mock, deduplication and full-queue errors need Integration tests, but the 3-second wall-clock timing under concurrent load and queue capacity enforcement both require System tests with real implementations.\n\nLet me reconsider behavior 4 though — the 3-second constraint with slow concurrent downstream processing is tricky. That's really about the handler's concurrency model and timing guarantees, which might actually need System-level testing to verify properly. In-process testing with supertest might miss some concurrency edge cases, but the real issue here is whether the event loop gets blocked by slow downstream work — that's testable in-process with artificial delays, so Integration should be sufficient. Actually, I think I need to bump behavior 4 to System since the failure mode is about real timing under concurrent HTTP load, which requires actual server connections and clients hitting it simultaneously.\n\nWait, let me reconsider: supertest can make concurrent requests in-process, wall-clock timing is just an assertion, and mocking slow downstream with real timers would catch the event loop blocking. I'm confident Integration works for behavior 4 — the failure is detectable without real infrastructure.\n\nSo my final breakdown is Integration for behaviors 1-6, and System for behavior 7 since it needs the real persistent queue to enforce capacity limits. Now I'm working through the probability distributions for each behavior, starting with signature validation where Unit testing the verifier alone is possible but Integration is more realistic since the handler and queue mock are involved.\n\nFor queue writes before returning 200, Integration dominates at 0.75 since that's where the ordering matters most. The 3-second wall-clock timing under concurrent load leans heavily toward System at 0.47 since you really need the actual performance characteristics under load. Deduplication and queue-full scenarios both favor Integration around 0.70, with deduplication having a small Unit component at 0.15 since the logic itself could be tested in isolation.\n\nFor persistent queue capacity, System takes the lead at 0.60 because you need to understand actual storage behavior and limits, not just the code paths. Now I'm reconsidering behavior 4 more carefully—the key failure mode is when the handler blocks on downstream processing, causing new concurrent requests to queue up and miss the 3-second deadline.\n\nTo properly test this, I'd need multiple concurrent HTTP requests hitting the server simultaneously while a mock downstream service intentionally delays responses. Integration testing with supertest can handle this if the queue consumer runs in-process, but if downstream is truly separate, System testing becomes necessary to catch real timing issues. I'll mark Integration as the minimum but note that System is likely needed depending on the architecture.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12794,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12794},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2ac743cc-9511-4c84-a50e-a9accf77b5fa","uuid":"24cb64ea-7974-4cac-894c-5535bbff3d31"}
