eeded. MOCK-HIDE: The mock queue records when it was called; comparing that timestamp to response-received time is sufficient to catch the failure. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — in-process response ordering is fully observable without a real network socket.","test_description":"Wire the handler with a mock queue that records the wall-clock time when its write method is invoked. Send a valid signed request via in-process test client and record the time the 200 response is received. Assert that queue write timestamp < response-received timestamp.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Handler returns HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing to finish","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure — handler blocking on downstream — only manifests when the handler is wired to a downstream that takes time; testing the handler in isolation cannot reveal this. REAL-INFRA: A mock downstream with an artificial delay (e.g., a Promise that resolves after 5 s) is sufficient; no real subprocess or network needed. MOCK-HIDE: The mock downstream's delay is the mechanism that exposes blocking; if it were replaced with a real downstream the same signal would appear but the mock captures it equally. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected — in-process async delay reproduces the exact failure mode (event-loop block vs. fire-and-forget).","test_description":"Wire the handler with a mock downstream whose processing Promise resolves after 5 seconds. Send a valid signed request and measure time-to-response. Assert the response arrives in under 1 second (well before the mock downstream resolves), confirming the handler did not await downstream completion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.32,"Agentic":